definitions.definition: ( transitive , intransitive ) To reach some destination or object, despite difficulty or toil (now usually intransitive, with preposition or locative adverb).
( transitive ) To triumph or achieve victory in (a game, a war, etc.).
( transitive ) To gain (a prize) by succeeding in competition or contest.
examples: to win the jackpot in a lottery;  to win a bottle of wine in a raffle

definitions.definition: ( transitive ) To obtain (someone) by wooing ; to make an ally or friend of (frequently with over ).

examples: Who would win in a fight between an octopus and a dolphin?

definitions.definition: ( intransitive ) To have power , coercion or control.
examples: Ever since the 2013 Boston Marathon bombing, Bostonians now run as "One Boston." The terrorists did not win .
The company hopes to win an order from the government worth over 5 million dollars.

definitions.definition: ( transitive ) To cause a victory for someone.
examples: The success of the economic policies should win Mr. Smith the next elections.
The policy success should win the elections for Mr. Smith.

definitions.definition: ( transitive , mining ) To extract (ore, coal, etc.).
( transitive , informal ) To defeat or surpass someone or something.
( computing , informal , intransitive ) To take priority.
examples: If the local filters conflict with the global filters, the global filters always win .
